    pearls: ["COP often mimics community-acquired pneumonia and is suspected when a patient fails to improve after 2-3 courses of antibiotics", "COP is highly responsive to corticosteroids but has a high relapse rate (25-50%) during taper - monitor closely", "Migratory consolidations on serial imaging are a hallmark finding that differentiates COP from infectious pneumonia"],
    quiz: [{ question: "A patient diagnosed with COP has been on prednisone for 8 weeks and symptoms have resolved. The provider begins tapering the steroid. What should the nurse monitor for?", options: ["Immediate anaphylaxis to prednisone", "Return of respiratory symptoms indicating relapse", "Development of pulmonary fibrosis", "Spontaneous pneumothorax"], correct: 1, rationale: "COP has a high relapse rate (25-50%) during corticosteroid taper. The nurse should closely monitor for return of cough, dyspnea, fever, and worsening oxygen saturation, which would indicate disease relapse requiring an increase in steroid dose." }]
